Here are both approaches.

**1. Register the route** in `AppShell.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
public AppShell()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
}
```

**2. Navigate from ProductListPage** — two options:

```csharp
// Approach A: query-string parameter (string ID only)
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?productId={product.Id}");

// Approach B: pass the full Product object
var parameters = new ShellNavigationQueryParameters
{
    { "product", product }
};
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", parameters);
```

**3. Receive both in the ViewModel** with `IQueryAttributable`:

```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    private string _productId;
    private Product _product;

    public string ProductId
    {
        get => _productId;
        set => SetProperty(ref _productId, value);
    }

    public Product Product
    {
        get => _product;
        set => SetProperty(ref _product, value);
    }

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach A: string parameter from query string
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var id))
        {
            ProductId = id.ToString();
            // Load the full product from a service using the ID
        }

        // Approach B: full object via ShellNavigationQueryParameters
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product p)
        {
            Product = p;
            ProductId = p.Id;
        }
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- **Approach A** — simple string via query string; good for deep-link–friendly IDs. The value arrives as a string.
- **Approach B** — uses `ShellNavigationQueryParameters` to pass the live object without serialization. The value arrives as the original type, so cast it.
- Both arrive in the same `ApplyQueryAttributes` dictionary — you can support both in one ViewModel.
- Always `await` the `GoToAsync` call to avoid race conditions.
